  FoodMenu(
      name: 'Spring Rolls',
      desc: '''Spring rolls are a popular appetizer or snack originating from various Asian cuisines, notably Chinese, Vietnamese, and Thai. These delectable rolls are typically made by wrapping a combination of fresh vegetables, herbs, protein, and sometimes noodles or rice in a thin, translucent wrapper made from rice flour or wheat.

The filling of spring rolls often includes a vibrant assortment of ingredients that provide a harmonious balance of flavors, colors, and textures. Common fillings may consist of crisp vegetables like shredded carrots, cabbage, bell peppers, bean sprouts, and cucumber. Additionally, protein options can include cooked shrimp, chicken, pork, or tofu, adding a savory element to the rolls. Fresh herbs such as cilantro, mint, and Thai basil are often added to provide a burst of aromatic freshness.

To assemble a spring roll, a sheet of the thin rice or wheat wrapper is briefly soaked in water to make it pliable. Then, a spoonful of the filling is placed in the center of the wrapper, and the sides are folded over the filling, followed by rolling to enclose it tightly. The resulting roll is typically cylindrical in shape, with the colorful ingredients visible through the translucent wrapper.

Spring rolls are commonly served fresh and uncooked, although some variations can be fried until crispy. The fresh version is often enjoyed with a dipping sauce on the side, such as sweet chili sauce, peanut sauce, hoisin sauce, or a combination of soy sauce and lime juice. These sauces provide an additional layer of flavor and complement the rolls perfectly.

Spring rolls are loved for their light and refreshing nature, as well as their versatility. They are suitable for various dietary preferences, including vegetarian and gluten-free diets. The combination of fresh vegetables, herbs, and protein wrapped in a delicate wrapper creates a delightful contrast of textures and tastes, with each bite offering a satisfying crunch and a burst of flavors.

Due to their popularity, spring rolls can be found in restaurants, street food stalls, and even made at home. They are often served as appetizers, party snacks, or part of a larger meal. Their widespread appeal and delightful presentation make them a beloved dish enjoyed by many, both within Asia and around the world.''',
